titleproper.value:
Guide to the Archie Brown Photograph Collection
                    <num>ALBA.PHOTO.207</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Evan Daniel

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2012-03-29T14:26-0400</date>

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: Archie Brown (1911-1990), San Francisco waterfront unionist, Communist Party organizer, and active member of the Bay Area Post of the Veterans of the Abraham Lincoln Brigade, fought with the Abraham Lincoln Brigade in Spain and participated in the Battle of the Bulge during WWII. He served on the Executive Board of the International Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's Union, Local 10, was prosecuted under the Landrum-Griffin Act barring Communists from serving as elected union officials, and won a Supreme Court decision in 1965 that overturned this legislation. The collection contains photographs of Brown at Veterans' receptions, reunions and other events. The collection also contains negatives and slides.

p.value:
Published citations should take the following form: 
                <lb/>
                <lb/>Identification of item, date; Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; 
                <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives 
                <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library 
                <lb/>70 Washington Square South 
                <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.

For further biographical information on Archie Brown, and to review the scope and contents of his manuscript collection see, The Guide to the Archie Brown Papers, ALBA 207. This collection includes images acquired by Brown in the course of his service as a volunteer in Spain and images of Brown, and others, from before and after the Spanish Civil War.

<emph render="bold">Series II: Negatives and Slide</emph>. The 56 black and white negatives contain images of Archie and Hon Brown with their family in the United States. Only four negatives, of Brown's family/friends, match prints in the collection. The color slide contains an image of a woman [Esther Brown?].
